"A few years ago, during a meeting, someone stopped me to ask the difference between data analytics and data analysis. \n\nIt caught me off guard. I knew both terms but had never really thought about how to explain them clearly. That moment made me pause and reflect, and it ended up shaping the way I approach data and communicate ideas today.\n\nHere’s how I now think about it:\n• Data Analysis focuses on the past—it’s about studying historical data to uncover trends and insights.\n• Data Analytics goes a step further—it’s about using tools and techniques to analyze data for both current and future decisions.\n\nThink of it this way:\n\nAnalysis is understanding what happened.\nAnalytics is about using that understanding to guide what happens next.\n\nAnd, then there is the Business Analysis. Business analysts work at the intersection of data and business goals. They analyze processes, identify inefficiencies, and propose solutions that align with organizational objectives. Think requirements gathering, and stakeholder communication.\n\nIt’s a small but meaningful distinction that has helped me communicate more effectively with teams and stakeholders.\n\nHave you ever had to clarify terms like this? I’d love to hear your thoughts!\n\n.\n…more"
