"I’m not trying to hurt your feelings. I’m trying to help your career. Code is a means to an end that’s being rapidly commoditized.\n\nCode Quality != Data Quality\nCode Complexity != Model Capability\nCode doesn’t make models more reliable or information more actionable.\n\nData scientists don’t deploy the code used for model training to production. Once the model is trained, the value of the code that did it drops to nearly 0. Models are the asset and high-value artifacts.\n\nData engineers don’t deliver code to production. They ship data and information. Once the dataset and knowledge graph segment are complete, the value of the code that built them drops to nearly 0.\n\nThe amount of code and technical complexity required to train a model or implement a pipeline are plummeting. Reusable frameworks and tools handle most of the heavy lifting.\n\nValue is stored in knowledge graphs, ontologies, models, simulations, and agents. The highest-value skills don’t maximize the code’s value; they maximize the artifact’s value.\n\nFocus your career on the assets that code creates, or the skills you’re building a career on will suffer from rapid depreciation. Being technical means something very different today than it did 5 years ago.\n…more"
"Data Science Skills Every Professional Needs to Thrive in 2025\n\nIn today’s fast-paced, data-driven world, professionals across industries are recognizing the value of data science skills, even if they’re not data scientists. Whether you’re in marketing, finance, healthcare, or operations, understanding the fundamentals of data science can give you a competitive edge. Here are the essential skills every professional should consider honing:\n\n1. Data Literacy: The ability to read, analyze, and interpret data is non-negotiable. Start by learning how to extract insights from spreadsheets and dashboards.\n\n2. Basic Programming: Familiarity with Python or R can open doors to automation, data cleaning, and analysis. Even basic scripting can save hours of manual work.\n\n3. Statistical Thinking: Understanding key concepts like correlation, regression, and hypothesis testing helps you make data-driven decisions with confidence.\n\n4. Data Visualization: Mastering tools like Tableau or Power BI ensures you can present data in a way that’s compelling and easy to understand.\n\n5. Automation: Automation isn’t just for tech professionals. Tools like Zapier, Python scripts, or even Excel macros can streamline repetitive tasks, freeing up time for strategic thinking.\n\nThe beauty of automation? It transforms time management, allowing you to focus on high-impact work while maintaining a healthy work-life balance. Imagine delegating routine tasks to a script while you tackle creative problem-solving or spend quality time with loved ones.\n\nBy embracing these skills, you’ll not only enhance your productivity but also position yourself as a forward-thinking professional ready to lead in the digital age.\n\nLet’s invest in these skills today to unlock tomorrow’s opportunities.\n\n…more"
