"Looking to create dates in different languages? Here's how they stack up between the most popular data science and data analytics languages.\n\nBy default, I tend to automatically think of three dimensions for dates (year, month, and day), and conversely six dimensions for date/times (year, month, day, hour, minute, and second). We can see from the comparison below that this approach works for most languages.\n\nHowever, SQL date/times require seven components for the DATETIMEFROMPARTS function and eight conversely for the DATETIME2FROMPARTS function. So, I resultingly often forget the seventh and eighth parameters for these functions when I write SQL code (and sometimes even run the code before realizing it returns errors if the IDE doesn't catch it before then).\n\nThese times are also time zone agnostic! Incorporating time zones is a topic (a big and often complex one at that) for another time and more discussion in the future.\n…more"
