"If you are learning analytics, then one of the most important skills to have is -> Data Cleaning\n\nWhether it is data engineering or data analysis or data science, the ability to clean & transform the data would come on the top of the list. The technical process where data cleaning happens is called ""ETL"" (Extract, Transform, and Load)\n\nHere are some of the popular tools for ETL (not in any order) :\n1) Microsoft Power Query (Excel & Power BI)\n2) Informatica PowerCenter\n3) Talend Data Integration\n4) IBM InfoSphere DataStage\n5) Microsoft SQL Server Integration Services (SSIS)\n6) Apache Spark\netc.\n\nBelow are some of the most popular data cleaning & data transformation techniques used.\n\nMS EXCEL, Power Query, Power BI skills for Business Intelligence # Microsoft SQL Server#🎖Power BI ✨Data Analyst 🎖Excel 🏵Data Scientist 🐫Big Data 🏀RPA 🏆SQL 🐍Python\n…more"
"When I started learning Data Engineering, I made a huge mistake.\n\n\nI got overwhelmed by the endless tech stack, batch vs. real-time streaming, open-source vs. cloud services, and ETL tools with multiple implementations (Apache Spark, Databricks, Flink, etc.).\n\nI didn’t know what to choose and what to ignore. It felt like running in circles, learning everything but mastering nothing.\n\nAfter solving real problems, working on projects, and understanding how companies operate, I had a realization\n\nThe tech stack is not the priority.\n\nIt’s all about the company’s objectives, scalability needs, cost-effectiveness, and the type of data they handle.\n\nWe choose tools based on the problem we’re solving, not just because they’re popular.\n\n\nIf I could start from scratch, this would be my roadmap\n\nUnderstand Big Data basics – What it is, data sources, and the 5 Vs (Volume, Velocity, Variety, Veracity, Value).\nLearn Distributed Systems – How large-scale data processing works.\nMaster SQL – The backbone of data engineering.\nGet comfortable with Python – You don’t need to be an expert, but you should be fluent.\nUnderstand Cloud Services (AWS/Azure/GCP) – Data isn’t stored locally anymore.\nLearn Apache Spark/Flink – The go-to for large-scale data processing.\nUnderstand Kafka – Streaming and real-time data movement.\nKnow Hadoop – Even if modern systems have evolved, it’s a foundation for big data.\nLearn - Databases/Datawarehouses/Datalakes\n\nIf you’re starting, don’t fall into the trap of trying to learn everything at once. Focus on foundations, then pick tools based on real-world needs.\n\n…more"
