"I talked with 5 data science major students from different programs and find out most of them don't even know the roles&responsibilities of different DS roles. \n\nMany new grad students reached out and tell me it's very difficult to find a data science role no matter how hard they've practiced coding. After talking with them, I find they cannot even distinguish the differences between data engineers, data scientists, or database management analyst. Actually I even feel it's mandatory to understand the complete operations workflow if someone really want to land a role in this field.\n\nHere is my short summaries on these roles.\n1. data engineer: basically build the data operations pipeline. The core skills are the understanding of big data technologies, coding in Python/SQL and ETL.\n2. database management: maintain and optimize the database. This function designs the database, deploy the new usage needs and support the business functions. Python/SQL is required.\n3. data analyst: this role is to support the business team to analyze the business issues and provide analytics-driven solutions.\n4. data scientists: This role responsible to develop and optimize the models and methodologies. The person need strong coding(in Python, SQL and R) and statistics skills.\n\nThe workflow is....data engineer and database manager prepare the data for data scientist. Then data scientists build the algorithms and data analyst apply the algorithms to solve the business problems.\n\nHave more questions about data science? Follow me to get the daily career tips!\n\n…more"
